MqoQrPPZYc0.title: MAÑANA QUE YA NO ESTE GRUPO INNOVACION
MqoQrPPZYc0.description: "Mañana que ya no este contigo", se que me vas a extrañar,se que te voy a extrañar, mas para los dos entonces sera muy tarde..yo estare lejos de ti.,tu estaras lejos de mi y todo porque los dos asi lo decidimos..es tarde buscar culpables ya que los dos tuvimos el tiempo en nuentras manos..los dos jugamos con ese tiempo. Ahora el tiempo se cobra asi,nos separa y para siempre..ya no llores que yo hare lo mismo,solo te pido que los DIAS y las NOCHES que vivas hasta el final de tus DIAS., recuerda los mas lindos momentos que los dos vivimos ayer como si tu lo vivieras en este mismo instante,y recuerda los sufrimientos como un mal sueño.,y ahora mira al cielo y ruegale al creador que nos de otra oportunidad de vivir, de soñar,de volver amar, de tener esa nueva esperanza de ser feliz.,si de ser FELICES,esa FELICIDAD que los dos siempre soñamos y que jamas se nos cumplio ese gran deseo.,...pero al lado de otra persona que ni TU ni YO conocemos..solo unos extraños pero de eso estoy seguro que algun lugar,algun dia hay alguien esperandonos "Mañana que ya no este contigo" ..HASTA SIEMPRE AMOR MIO.

YNhe82a5Dvk.title: HiDef: UP 844 and UP 1982 Leads the Little Rock Express
YNhe82a5Dvk.description:
I am proud to say that I have finally caught Union Pacific 844. Legsbluetrain and I drove 5 hours up to Poplar Bluff, MO to intercept UP 844 and the Little Rock Express. When we got there, it had already arrived and it was backing into the Amtrak station in which it stayed there for about two hours. We made sure to leave at least an hour before it did so that we could find a location to catch it at. We ended up going to Neelyville, MO. The whole chase was very very crowded with other railfans. The first shot was done in Neelyville. I used my two cameras to catch it there. After it passed, we rushed back across the state line to Corning, AR to catch it again. Luckily, it had to stop there and wait on a northbound coal train. I also decided to film the coal train's arrival and the meet. After the Coal train cleared, I recorded 844's departure from Corning. After that point, it was very very hard to keep up with the ol' girl. It didn't help any that the road left the tracks for a while. When the road finally came back to the tracks, 844 was at least 3 miles or so ahead of us. We had to do some serious "booking". We managed to get ahead of it and I was barely able to catch it at a rural crossing south of Knobel, AR. I had no time to set up a tripod there. It ended up making another whistle stop in Walnut Ridge, AR so that gave us plenty of time to get ahead of it again. We then caught it in Alicia, AR. I used two cameras at that location also. After passing through Alicia, it made an unscheduled stop. That was also very fortunate for us. We got ahead of it again and ended up beating it to Bald Knob. We heard that it was still about 15 miles out so we set up at a private crossing north of Bald Knob. Once again I used two cameras. Since they are not required to blow at a private crossing, legsbluetrain and I signaled for him to blow the whistle for us as he was coming and he kindly did so. After catching him there, we somehow managed to beat his arrival into Bald Knob. It was the best train chase I've ever had. I apologize about all of the people in most of my shots. It was very hard to avoid that. 

I hope that you all enjoy.

wSKz30b5TkA.title: #43- Sea-Glassing fretboard edges
wSKz30b5TkA.description: A lot of players comment on the comfort of our necks. Folks, this is the secret! I call it 'Sea-Glassing'. I remember back in the day playing an old LP 'Junior' that had come through our shop and it had an incredible feeling neck! It didn't take much thinking to realize that it was because of the fretboards totally worn edges. Since then I have been rounding in the edges of my fretboards while the neck is still square. The footage is not the greatest but I promise that if you incorporate this operation into your next build you will be amazed in the end when you're playing it! Cutter radius is a matter of preference, I prefer a 3/4" radius and further round by hand later on. Just remember that a little bit is a lot a bit when it comes to guitar making. Happy cutting!

Watch more Home Back Workout for Men videos: http://www.howcast.com/videos/503081-How-to-Do-a-Standing-Row-Back-Workout



Hi guys, this is Max Tapper again for HowCast. And what I'm going to show you guys how to do today, is a standing cable row.

This row is going to be targeted at working your lats, your biceps, your rear delts, your rhomboids, everything in that area. And we're also going to have a little bit of load on our legs, so we're going to get a small amount of work there, too. But let me show you how that's going to look, Okay?

So we're going to use this cable machine. We're going to grab a hold, and we're going to actually give ourselves a nice dip. So we need to have our knees bent, our hips out, take that pressure off our lower back. So now we're just going to row, back. Slow forward, allow your shoulders to retract. Pinch, row, slow out, shoulders forward again, slow back, pinch. Now, that is a standing cable row.

The standing cable row is an excellent exercise, but because of the requirements on your legs and your lower back, you're not going to be able to lift a huge, huge, huge amount of weight. So this would not be one of the main exercises that I would choose to focus on your back. I would still do something like a seated row, pull-up, pull-down, this would be a peripheral exercise that I would do after that. But this is definitely an excellent exercise, targets a lot of other muscles and it also targets your legs and your core at the same time, while it's touching your big back muscles.

In an exercise like this, I love to work in the rep range of between ten and 12. Basically, ten and 12, is the hypertrophy range, where you actually build a lot bigger muscles, and you also get stronger. So ten to 12 is a range I love to be in. Let's put as much weight as you can possibly handle up to ten to 12, in perfect, perfect form. Okay? So if you start to lose your balance and lean forward, the weight's too heavy. So basically what you're going to be doing by sitting down is counter-balancing whatever's going on here, and allowing yourself to work your lats. Alright?

So guys, remember. This is not going to be one of the prime movers. This is definitely not one of the exercises that you can lift tons and tons of weight on, because of the requirement on your other muscles. But it's definitely an excellent one, and it's something that you should put into your back workout.
